class Solution {
public:
    bool isValid(string s) {
        int n = s.length();
        stack<char>st;
        int i = 0;
        while(i<n){
            if(s[i]=='(' || s[i]=='{' || s[i]=='['){
                st.push(s[i]);
            }
            else{
                if(st.empty()) return false;
                if(s[i]==')' && st.top()=='(' || s[i]=='}' && st.top()=='{'||s[i]==']' && st.top()=='['){
                    st.pop();
                }
                else return false;
            }
            i++;
        }
        return st.empty();
    }
};

"Idea:
The idea is to use a stack to keep track of opening brackets while traversing the string.
Whenever an opening bracket (, {, or [ appears, push it into the stack.
When a closing bracket is encountered, check if the stack is empty; if yes, the string is invalid.
Otherwise, compare the current closing bracket with the top element of the stack.
If both brackets form a valid pair, remove the opening bracket from the stack using pop().
If the brackets do not match, immediately return false because the order is incorrect.
After processing the entire string, the stack should be empty for the string to be valid
"
#Time Complexity:- O(n)             Space Complexity:- O(n)
